WEBVTT

00:00:00.000 --> 00:00:02.450 align:middle line:90%
[SQUEAKING]

00:00:02.450 --> 00:00:04.410 align:middle line:90%
[RUSTLING]

00:00:04.410 --> 00:00:07.350 align:middle line:90%
[CLICKING]

00:00:07.350 --> 00:00:09.520 align:middle line:90%


00:00:09.520 --> 00:00:12.800 align:middle line:84%
TOBIAS COLDING:
Just begin with--

00:00:12.800 --> 00:00:31.800 align:middle line:84%
so if we have a metric space
here, then a cover of x

00:00:31.800 --> 00:00:51.080 align:middle line:84%
is a collection of subsets u
alpha so that the x is contained

00:00:51.080 --> 00:00:55.120 align:middle line:90%
in the union of u alpha.

00:00:55.120 --> 00:01:03.470 align:middle line:84%
So that's a cover
of X and likewise,

00:01:03.470 --> 00:01:11.070 align:middle line:84%
if a here is a subset
of x, then u alpha

00:01:11.070 --> 00:01:23.630 align:middle line:84%
is a cover of a if a here is
in the union of the u alpha.

00:01:23.630 --> 00:01:29.950 align:middle line:84%
So that's what it means to cover
the whole set or just a subset.

00:01:29.950 --> 00:01:35.990 align:middle line:84%
Then there are some covers that
are particularly important,

00:01:35.990 --> 00:01:38.570 align:middle line:90%
and those are the open covers.

00:01:38.570 --> 00:01:55.840 align:middle line:84%
So a open cover is a cover
that consists of open subsets.

00:01:55.840 --> 00:02:02.110 align:middle line:90%


00:02:02.110 --> 00:02:07.190 align:middle line:84%
And then finally, we
have that, so if again,

00:02:07.190 --> 00:02:13.230 align:middle line:84%
x,d is a metric space,
a here is a subset of x,

00:02:13.230 --> 00:02:39.630 align:middle line:84%
then we say that a is compact
if every open cover of a has

00:02:39.630 --> 00:02:51.350 align:middle line:90%
a finite subcover, OK.

00:02:51.350 --> 00:02:56.110 align:middle line:84%
And one thing we proved last
time, was that if you have--

00:02:56.110 --> 00:02:59.380 align:middle line:90%


00:02:59.380 --> 00:03:13.620 align:middle line:84%
a so we proved last time, that
if you have a here is compact,

00:03:13.620 --> 00:03:26.330 align:middle line:90%
then a is bounded and closed.

00:03:26.330 --> 00:03:34.460 align:middle line:90%


00:03:34.460 --> 00:03:37.460 align:middle line:84%
Right, so it's a is a
closed subset, meaning

00:03:37.460 --> 00:03:44.380 align:middle line:84%
that the complement
is open, and a itself

00:03:44.380 --> 00:03:49.900 align:middle line:84%
is contained in some large ball
centered at some point in x.

00:03:49.900 --> 00:03:55.780 align:middle line:84%
Now, the converse is
not the case always.

00:03:55.780 --> 00:04:19.180 align:middle line:84%
So In Rn the usual
metric, Euclidean metric,

00:04:19.180 --> 00:04:32.300 align:middle line:84%
the converse is the case
but in general not--

00:04:32.300 --> 00:04:33.230 align:middle line:90%
but not in general.

00:04:33.230 --> 00:04:42.400 align:middle line:90%


00:04:42.400 --> 00:04:50.220 align:middle line:84%
And so we looked at one
example on this last time.

00:04:50.220 --> 00:04:52.930 align:middle line:84%
So we looked at the
following example.

00:04:52.930 --> 00:04:55.450 align:middle line:84%
But it was a rather
trivial example

00:04:55.450 --> 00:04:58.250 align:middle line:90%
that if you take x here--

00:04:58.250 --> 00:05:05.770 align:middle line:84%
if you take the space x to be,
say, the interval from 0 to 1,

00:05:05.770 --> 00:05:10.530 align:middle line:84%
and the metric here, this
here is the usual metric,

00:05:10.530 --> 00:05:15.530 align:middle line:84%
so the distance
between two elements

00:05:15.530 --> 00:05:20.930 align:middle line:84%
here is just the norm
of the difference.

00:05:20.930 --> 00:05:27.650 align:middle line:84%
And then well, x is the
whole set, so with this here,

00:05:27.650 --> 00:05:28.830 align:middle line:90%
x is the whole set.

00:05:28.830 --> 00:05:32.530 align:middle line:84%
So x here, if this here
is the metric space,

00:05:32.530 --> 00:05:38.650 align:middle line:84%
then x is, by definition, closed
because the whole set is closed.

00:05:38.650 --> 00:05:41.450 align:middle line:84%
It's not closed
as a subset of r,

00:05:41.450 --> 00:05:48.410 align:middle line:84%
but if the metric space just
is x, then it is closed,

00:05:48.410 --> 00:05:52.490 align:middle line:90%
and it's bounded--

00:05:52.490 --> 00:05:55.570 align:middle line:90%
and bounded.

00:05:55.570 --> 00:05:58.890 align:middle line:84%
In particular,
this interval here

00:05:58.890 --> 00:06:05.610 align:middle line:84%
is contained in the ball of
radius one half around one half.

00:06:05.610 --> 00:06:08.930 align:middle line:84%
But it's actually equal
to that ball, if you will.

00:06:08.930 --> 00:06:15.790 align:middle line:84%
So it's definitely bounded,
but it's not compact, right?

00:06:15.790 --> 00:06:16.840 align:middle line:90%
So it's not compact.

00:06:16.840 --> 00:06:22.050 align:middle line:90%


00:06:22.050 --> 00:06:31.610 align:middle line:84%
Because you can write x here
as the union of 1 over n to 1.

00:06:31.610 --> 00:06:38.215 align:middle line:84%
And now you take the union
over all positive integers.

00:06:38.215 --> 00:06:41.050 align:middle line:84%
But if you only take
finitely many of them,

00:06:41.050 --> 00:06:45.490 align:middle line:84%
then you don't get all the
way down to zero, right?

00:06:45.490 --> 00:06:47.390 align:middle line:90%
So it's not a union.

00:06:47.390 --> 00:06:49.440 align:middle line:90%
It's union of all of these.

00:06:49.440 --> 00:06:53.800 align:middle line:90%
Each of these r is open, But.

00:06:53.800 --> 00:07:00.200 align:middle line:84%
There's no finite union of
those sets that cover x.

00:07:00.200 --> 00:07:07.640 align:middle line:84%
A more interesting example
is that-- suppose you take--

00:07:07.640 --> 00:07:12.520 align:middle line:84%
suppose you take-- so here's
another example that we

00:07:12.520 --> 00:07:17.680 align:middle line:84%
didn't get to last time, that if
you take the continuous function

00:07:17.680 --> 00:07:23.380 align:middle line:84%
on the unit interval,
and so if you take--

00:07:23.380 --> 00:07:30.640 align:middle line:84%
and now we use this metric
that we have looked at before,

00:07:30.640 --> 00:07:36.400 align:middle line:84%
where the distance
between two functions

00:07:36.400 --> 00:07:47.640 align:middle line:84%
is the max over x in this
interval here of the norm of f

00:07:47.640 --> 00:07:50.006 align:middle line:90%
of x minus g of x.

00:07:50.006 --> 00:07:53.080 align:middle line:90%


00:07:53.080 --> 00:07:57.900 align:middle line:84%
We've already seen that
this here is a nice metric.

00:07:57.900 --> 00:08:01.320 align:middle line:90%
And if I now look at--

00:08:01.320 --> 00:08:06.720 align:middle line:84%
in this metric, I
look at the unit ball,

00:08:06.720 --> 00:08:12.040 align:middle line:84%
so I'm looking at the
closed unit ball, which

00:08:12.040 --> 00:08:19.800 align:middle line:84%
means that I'm looking at
the set of functions here,

00:08:19.800 --> 00:08:26.240 align:middle line:84%
so that the distance of
f to the function that

00:08:26.240 --> 00:08:31.800 align:middle line:84%
is constant equal to
zero, this distance here,

00:08:31.800 --> 00:08:35.419 align:middle line:90%
is less or equal to one.

00:08:35.419 --> 00:08:38.039 align:middle line:90%


00:08:38.039 --> 00:08:41.440 align:middle line:84%
So I'm looking
here at the subset

00:08:41.440 --> 00:08:47.590 align:middle line:84%
of the continuous
function on this interval,

00:08:47.590 --> 00:08:52.590 align:middle line:84%
so that the distance to the
zero function is at most one.

00:08:52.590 --> 00:08:54.810 align:middle line:90%
So let me just write this out.

00:08:54.810 --> 00:08:58.110 align:middle line:84%
So this means that
this is the function

00:08:58.110 --> 00:09:04.190 align:middle line:84%
f in this continuous
function here,

00:09:04.190 --> 00:09:11.630 align:middle line:84%
so that the max
of f of x minus 0,

00:09:11.630 --> 00:09:19.190 align:middle line:84%
so I don't really have to write
0, is less than or equal to 1.

00:09:19.190 --> 00:09:23.030 align:middle line:90%


00:09:23.030 --> 00:09:28.790 align:middle line:84%
Now, this set again, this set
here, is what we denote by the--

00:09:28.790 --> 00:09:32.550 align:middle line:84%
this is the closed unit ball
because you have less than

00:09:32.550 --> 00:09:33.930 align:middle line:90%
or equal to here.

00:09:33.930 --> 00:09:39.870 align:middle line:84%
And the closed unit ball, the
open unit ball we have written,

00:09:39.870 --> 00:09:44.750 align:middle line:84%
this is now the function that
is identically equal to 0.

00:09:44.750 --> 00:09:47.750 align:middle line:84%
The open unit ball,
we wrote like this.

00:09:47.750 --> 00:09:51.710 align:middle line:84%
This is if you have
strict inequality.

00:09:51.710 --> 00:09:56.030 align:middle line:84%
And to denote that
it's less or equal to,

00:09:56.030 --> 00:09:57.890 align:middle line:90%
I'm just putting a bar here.

00:09:57.890 --> 00:10:01.950 align:middle line:90%


00:10:01.950 --> 00:10:04.310 align:middle line:84%
And so we already
know that this thing

00:10:04.310 --> 00:10:06.830 align:middle line:84%
here, if you take
a metric space,

00:10:06.830 --> 00:10:09.970 align:middle line:84%
and you're looking at a
closed unit ball like this,

00:10:09.970 --> 00:10:13.210 align:middle line:84%
we already proved that
this here is closed.

00:10:13.210 --> 00:10:16.590 align:middle line:84%
Because we proved directly,
using the triangle inequality,

00:10:16.590 --> 00:10:18.340 align:middle line:90%
that the complement is open.

00:10:18.340 --> 00:10:20.980 align:middle line:90%


00:10:20.980 --> 00:10:24.650 align:middle line:90%
OK, so this is a closed subset.

00:10:24.650 --> 00:10:28.000 align:middle line:84%
It's obviously bounded because
it's actually even just a ball,

00:10:28.000 --> 00:10:28.500 align:middle line:90%
right?

00:10:28.500 --> 00:10:33.990 align:middle line:90%


00:10:33.990 --> 00:10:35.310 align:middle line:90%
But I claim that--

00:10:35.310 --> 00:10:37.170 align:middle line:90%
so it's closed.

00:10:37.170 --> 00:10:42.220 align:middle line:84%
It's bounded, but
it's not compact.

00:10:42.220 --> 00:10:49.660 align:middle line:84%
And here's a interesting
example of a sequence

00:10:49.660 --> 00:10:51.680 align:middle line:90%
of elements in this ball.

00:10:51.680 --> 00:11:01.540 align:middle line:84%
So I will now construct for each
n, which is a natural number,

00:11:01.540 --> 00:11:10.700 align:middle line:84%
we construct a
function fn in this

00:11:10.700 --> 00:11:14.300 align:middle line:84%
that is a continuous function
on this unit interval.

00:11:14.300 --> 00:11:18.490 align:middle line:84%
And the function f will
be given as follows.

00:11:18.490 --> 00:11:23.820 align:middle line:90%


00:11:23.820 --> 00:11:33.670 align:middle line:90%
It will be one from when--

00:11:33.670 --> 00:11:37.340 align:middle line:90%


00:11:37.340 --> 00:11:37.880 align:middle line:90%
let's see.

00:11:37.880 --> 00:11:48.190 align:middle line:84%
Let me make it 0/ I
guess it doesn't matter.

00:11:48.190 --> 00:11:56.530 align:middle line:84%
I'll make it one when x here
is between 1 over n plus 1.

00:11:56.530 --> 00:12:01.170 align:middle line:84%
No, no, I would
make it equal to 1

00:12:01.170 --> 00:12:06.850 align:middle line:84%
when x here is bigger or equal
to 0 and less than or equal to 1

00:12:06.850 --> 00:12:08.190 align:middle line:90%
over n plus 1.

00:12:08.190 --> 00:12:10.970 align:middle line:90%


00:12:10.970 --> 00:12:21.010 align:middle line:84%
Then I'll make it when x here is
bigger than or equal to 1 over n

00:12:21.010 --> 00:12:28.650 align:middle line:84%
but less or equal to 1,
then I'll set it equal to 0.

00:12:28.650 --> 00:12:34.250 align:middle line:84%
And then you see now,
I wanted to do so--

00:12:34.250 --> 00:12:36.310 align:middle line:90%
so let's look at it.

00:12:36.310 --> 00:12:54.930 align:middle line:84%
So this function here is
if you draw this function--

00:12:54.930 --> 00:12:58.710 align:middle line:90%
so I have here 1.

00:12:58.710 --> 00:13:00.770 align:middle line:90%
Here I have 0.

00:13:00.770 --> 00:13:08.190 align:middle line:84%
And this function is 1
up to 1 over n plus 1.

00:13:08.190 --> 00:13:11.850 align:middle line:84%
Maybe I'll draw it a
little bit further out.

00:13:11.850 --> 00:13:19.170 align:middle line:84%
Let me actually make the
picture bigger, so like that.

00:13:19.170 --> 00:13:22.170 align:middle line:90%
Here I have 1.

00:13:22.170 --> 00:13:27.810 align:middle line:90%
Here I have 1 over n plus 1.

00:13:27.810 --> 00:13:32.090 align:middle line:90%
And here I have 1 over n.

00:13:32.090 --> 00:13:35.120 align:middle line:84%
And the function is
supposed to be 1 here.

00:13:35.120 --> 00:13:38.520 align:middle line:90%


00:13:38.520 --> 00:13:48.240 align:middle line:84%
And then it's supposed to die
off between here and here.

00:13:48.240 --> 00:13:51.760 align:middle line:84%
And I choose it to
die off linearly.

00:13:51.760 --> 00:13:54.160 align:middle line:90%
And then it's 0 here.

00:13:54.160 --> 00:13:57.520 align:middle line:84%
So if it's going
down linearly, this

00:13:57.520 --> 00:14:00.840 align:middle line:84%
means that I have my--
what is the difference

00:14:00.840 --> 00:14:02.920 align:middle line:90%
between these two?

00:14:02.920 --> 00:14:07.220 align:middle line:84%
It's 1 over n minus
1 over n plus 1.

00:14:07.220 --> 00:14:09.320 align:middle line:90%
This is this distance here.

00:14:09.320 --> 00:14:13.640 align:middle line:84%
And so this here, putting it on
a common denominator n plus 1

00:14:13.640 --> 00:14:16.000 align:middle line:90%
over n times n plus 1.

00:14:16.000 --> 00:14:18.280 align:middle line:90%
This is what you get from this.

00:14:18.280 --> 00:14:22.240 align:middle line:84%
And if you put it on the common
denominator for the second one,

00:14:22.240 --> 00:14:24.160 align:middle line:90%
this is what you get here.

00:14:24.160 --> 00:14:30.240 align:middle line:84%
And so this is just
1 over n like this.

00:14:30.240 --> 00:14:34.200 align:middle line:84%
And so this is
this distance here.

00:14:34.200 --> 00:14:39.820 align:middle line:84%
And so if I define
the function to be--

00:14:39.820 --> 00:14:46.260 align:middle line:90%
so I'm setting it equal to this.

00:14:46.260 --> 00:14:49.520 align:middle line:84%
And now in between
when x here is

00:14:49.520 --> 00:14:55.120 align:middle line:84%
bigger or equal to 1 over n plus
1 and less or equal to 1 over n,

00:14:55.120 --> 00:15:11.640 align:middle line:84%
I will set it equal to 1
minus n times n plus 1 times--

00:15:11.640 --> 00:15:13.850 align:middle line:90%
sorry, let me make more space.

00:15:13.850 --> 00:15:19.680 align:middle line:90%


00:15:19.680 --> 00:15:22.600 align:middle line:90%
Yeah, let me make more space.

00:15:22.600 --> 00:15:27.180 align:middle line:84%
So here, this here was when
0 is less or equal to x, less

00:15:27.180 --> 00:15:30.280 align:middle line:90%
or equal to 1 over n plus 1.

00:15:30.280 --> 00:15:38.110 align:middle line:84%
This is when x here is
between these two numbers.

00:15:38.110 --> 00:15:42.470 align:middle line:84%
And this here is when x
is larger than 1 over n

00:15:42.470 --> 00:15:46.810 align:middle line:84%
And it's x is always in the
interval between 0 and 1.

00:15:46.810 --> 00:15:59.550 align:middle line:84%
And here, I'm choosing it's x
minus and then 1 over n plus 1.

00:15:59.550 --> 00:16:06.870 align:middle line:84%
So you see that if you take
x to be 1 over n plus 1,

00:16:06.870 --> 00:16:08.830 align:middle line:90%
then here contributes 0.

00:16:08.830 --> 00:16:11.750 align:middle line:84%
So at this left point,
this here is equal

00:16:11.750 --> 00:16:15.670 align:middle line:84%
to-- it's the function is
equal to 1, as it should be.

00:16:15.670 --> 00:16:19.590 align:middle line:84%
And when x here is at
the other endpoint,

00:16:19.590 --> 00:16:23.350 align:middle line:84%
then this here becomes
exactly 1 over this,

00:16:23.350 --> 00:16:24.990 align:middle line:90%
So this whole thing becomes 0.

00:16:24.990 --> 00:16:28.230 align:middle line:90%


00:16:28.230 --> 00:16:36.370 align:middle line:84%
So this function here I drew, is
if you write it down precisely,

00:16:36.370 --> 00:16:37.650 align:middle line:90%
this is what the function is.

00:16:37.650 --> 00:16:46.340 align:middle line:90%


00:16:46.340 --> 00:16:57.230 align:middle line:84%
And now if I'm looking at
the difference between two

00:16:57.230 --> 00:17:01.550 align:middle line:84%
such functions, so
for the next one--

00:17:01.550 --> 00:17:04.030 align:middle line:90%
you see the next one here?

00:17:04.030 --> 00:17:06.050 align:middle line:90%
The next one here is--

00:17:06.050 --> 00:17:10.430 align:middle line:90%
so this here is fn.

00:17:10.430 --> 00:17:12.130 align:middle line:90%
This is how fn looks like.

00:17:12.130 --> 00:17:18.069 align:middle line:84%
If I now look at fn plus 1,
this start off being it's

00:17:18.069 --> 00:17:21.390 align:middle line:84%
0 to the right of
this thing here.

00:17:21.390 --> 00:17:28.950 align:middle line:84%
And then it's 1 once
you get to n plus 2.

00:17:28.950 --> 00:17:34.540 align:middle line:84%
So the next function
looks like this.

00:17:34.540 --> 00:17:36.440 align:middle line:84%
I don't know if there's
any color chalk,

00:17:36.440 --> 00:17:42.960 align:middle line:84%
but this thing here,
that's the next function.

00:17:42.960 --> 00:17:48.540 align:middle line:84%
So the first function
is this function here.

00:17:48.540 --> 00:17:50.540 align:middle line:84%
That's a graph of
the first function.

00:17:50.540 --> 00:17:53.420 align:middle line:90%
The next one is this one here.

00:17:53.420 --> 00:17:56.300 align:middle line:90%


00:17:56.300 --> 00:18:02.500 align:middle line:84%
And so if you're now looking at
the distance between fn and fn

00:18:02.500 --> 00:18:09.020 align:middle line:84%
plus 1, the distance
here was the sup

00:18:09.020 --> 00:18:11.440 align:middle line:90%
of the difference of the two.

00:18:11.440 --> 00:18:18.980 align:middle line:84%
This here was just
a max of f of--

00:18:18.980 --> 00:18:19.720 align:middle line:90%
like this.

00:18:19.720 --> 00:18:22.900 align:middle line:90%


00:18:22.900 --> 00:18:25.740 align:middle line:84%
It was just a max
of this, right?

00:18:25.740 --> 00:18:29.620 align:middle line:84%
And now I know that these
two numbers is always

00:18:29.620 --> 00:18:31.620 align:middle line:90%
between 0 and 1.

00:18:31.620 --> 00:18:36.640 align:middle line:90%
So this max here is at most 1.

00:18:36.640 --> 00:18:40.540 align:middle line:84%
But if I now evaluate it,
if I'm now looking at--

00:18:40.540 --> 00:18:42.500 align:middle line:84%
if I now just
evaluate it, if I'm

00:18:42.500 --> 00:18:48.460 align:middle line:84%
looking at fn, and now I just
evaluate it in this point

00:18:48.460 --> 00:18:53.580 align:middle line:84%
here, in this point
1 over n plus 1,

00:18:53.580 --> 00:18:59.820 align:middle line:84%
so if I'm looking at this
thing here fn plus 1,

00:18:59.820 --> 00:19:02.580 align:middle line:90%
1 over n plus 1--

00:19:02.580 --> 00:19:07.820 align:middle line:84%
you see this value here,
this first function here,

00:19:07.820 --> 00:19:10.340 align:middle line:90%
and at this point, it's 1.

00:19:10.340 --> 00:19:12.500 align:middle line:90%
This here is 1.

00:19:12.500 --> 00:19:15.940 align:middle line:84%
But for the next one, you
see at that point it's 0.

00:19:15.940 --> 00:19:19.220 align:middle line:90%


00:19:19.220 --> 00:19:26.210 align:middle line:84%
So this means that this max
here, is for all n and n plus 1,

00:19:26.210 --> 00:19:31.330 align:middle line:90%
is actually equal to 1.

00:19:31.330 --> 00:19:44.580 align:middle line:84%
And so now if you
look at the balls--

00:19:44.580 --> 00:19:52.530 align:middle line:90%


00:19:52.530 --> 00:19:55.970 align:middle line:84%
so now, in particular,
if I'm looking

00:19:55.970 --> 00:20:01.250 align:middle line:84%
at the balls of radius
one half, suppose

00:20:01.250 --> 00:20:05.150 align:middle line:84%
I'm looking at the ball of
radius one half around--

00:20:05.150 --> 00:20:10.850 align:middle line:84%
so this is an open
ball, so around fn.

00:20:10.850 --> 00:20:12.590 align:middle line:84%
Because this here
is an open ball,

00:20:12.590 --> 00:20:15.050 align:middle line:84%
so it means that's strictly
less than one half,

00:20:15.050 --> 00:20:20.370 align:middle line:84%
so this means that fn plus
1 is not in that ball.

00:20:20.370 --> 00:20:23.210 align:middle line:90%


00:20:23.210 --> 00:20:24.150 align:middle line:90%
So it's not in.

00:20:24.150 --> 00:20:26.730 align:middle line:90%
So it's not in that ball.

00:20:26.730 --> 00:20:32.410 align:middle line:84%
And so now it's easy to
see that all of these balls

00:20:32.410 --> 00:20:36.690 align:middle line:90%
here are disjoint.

00:20:36.690 --> 00:20:40.930 align:middle line:84%
So all of these balls
here will be disjoint.

00:20:40.930 --> 00:20:42.570 align:middle line:90%
They're all disjoint.

00:20:42.570 --> 00:20:49.730 align:middle line:84%
And so if you're looking at if
you can write this initial ball,

00:20:49.730 --> 00:20:52.290 align:middle line:84%
this ball here, this
was this close ball

00:20:52.290 --> 00:20:55.130 align:middle line:84%
that we started with
in the beginning,

00:20:55.130 --> 00:21:00.170 align:middle line:90%
you can write it as a union.

00:21:00.170 --> 00:21:05.010 align:middle line:84%
You can write it, of course,
as a union of half balls

00:21:05.010 --> 00:21:14.210 align:middle line:84%
where you take the
union over all centers,

00:21:14.210 --> 00:21:17.570 align:middle line:90%
all possible centers like this.

00:21:17.570 --> 00:21:21.250 align:middle line:84%
Because it's clearly
cover this set

00:21:21.250 --> 00:21:23.920 align:middle line:84%
because it contains
all the centers.

00:21:23.920 --> 00:21:27.800 align:middle line:84%
But that's already
the whole set.

00:21:27.800 --> 00:21:32.040 align:middle line:84%
But using this here, you
can see that there is not--

00:21:32.040 --> 00:21:36.080 align:middle line:84%
that you can't have
finitely many of these half

00:21:36.080 --> 00:21:39.360 align:middle line:90%
balls that cover the whole set.

00:21:39.360 --> 00:21:57.440 align:middle line:84%
So using the functions
fn, it follows easily

00:21:57.440 --> 00:22:13.070 align:middle line:84%
that finitely many of
these balls does not cover.

00:22:13.070 --> 00:22:19.960 align:middle line:90%


00:22:19.960 --> 00:22:22.670 align:middle line:90%
And let me just cover this here.

00:22:22.670 --> 00:22:25.430 align:middle line:90%
Why is this the case?

00:22:25.430 --> 00:22:30.710 align:middle line:84%
Actually, sometimes you put
the bar all the way across.

00:22:30.710 --> 00:22:33.230 align:middle line:90%
But I haven't done that.

00:22:33.230 --> 00:22:41.240 align:middle line:84%
OK, suppose for a
second, that you have--

00:22:41.240 --> 00:22:46.710 align:middle line:90%


00:22:46.710 --> 00:22:54.170 align:middle line:84%
suppose that you have a
ball here of radius one

00:22:54.170 --> 00:22:56.430 align:middle line:90%
half around some point.

00:22:56.430 --> 00:23:00.630 align:middle line:84%
And suppose that
you have a function,

00:23:00.630 --> 00:23:04.950 align:middle line:84%
g-- two functions g and
h that are in that ball,

00:23:04.950 --> 00:23:07.590 align:middle line:84%
just using that
it's a metric space.

00:23:07.590 --> 00:23:13.710 align:middle line:84%
So now we have that this
thing here, g, is strictly

00:23:13.710 --> 00:23:19.430 align:middle line:84%
less than one half, and
the distance from f to h

00:23:19.430 --> 00:23:22.470 align:middle line:90%
is strictly less than one half.

00:23:22.470 --> 00:23:24.890 align:middle line:84%
So now using the
triangle inequality,

00:23:24.890 --> 00:23:30.630 align:middle line:84%
we conclude that the distance
between this pair here, g and h,

00:23:30.630 --> 00:23:34.570 align:middle line:84%
is less than or equal to the
distance where you go over f.

00:23:34.570 --> 00:23:38.150 align:middle line:90%


00:23:38.150 --> 00:23:41.510 align:middle line:84%
And so this has strictly
less than one half

00:23:41.510 --> 00:23:45.430 align:middle line:84%
plus one half, so this
is strictly less than 1.

00:23:45.430 --> 00:23:48.310 align:middle line:84%
So you see from
this, in particular,

00:23:48.310 --> 00:23:53.550 align:middle line:84%
that if you take
such a ball here,

00:23:53.550 --> 00:24:09.110 align:middle line:84%
then you can't-- so it's
impossible to have that fn,

00:24:09.110 --> 00:24:12.350 align:middle line:90%
n fn plus 1.

00:24:12.350 --> 00:24:14.490 align:middle line:90%
It's impossible to have that.

00:24:14.490 --> 00:24:17.940 align:middle line:90%
They both are in that ball.

00:24:17.940 --> 00:24:20.940 align:middle line:84%
Because if they were
both in this ball, then

00:24:20.940 --> 00:24:23.360 align:middle line:84%
the distance would be
strictly less than 1.

00:24:23.360 --> 00:24:26.160 align:middle line:84%
And we've already seen
that distance is 1.

00:24:26.160 --> 00:24:32.340 align:middle line:84%
And this holds, not just
for fn and the next one,

00:24:32.340 --> 00:24:35.260 align:middle line:84%
but it holds for fn--
the same argument gives

00:24:35.260 --> 00:24:39.500 align:middle line:84%
that from fn and
any n larger than n,

00:24:39.500 --> 00:24:42.260 align:middle line:90%
this here would be impossible.

00:24:42.260 --> 00:24:44.980 align:middle line:84%
And so from this, it follows
that you can't have finitely

00:24:44.980 --> 00:24:51.900 align:middle line:90%
many that cover the ball, Yeah?

00:24:51.900 --> 00:24:55.820 align:middle line:84%
AUDIENCE: How do we know
that the union of all

00:24:55.820 --> 00:24:59.100 align:middle line:90%
of those functions and the one?

00:24:59.100 --> 00:25:01.500 align:middle line:84%
TOBIAS COLDING: Yeah,
so this is just--

00:25:01.500 --> 00:25:03.260 align:middle line:84%
and this is important
because we're going

00:25:03.260 --> 00:25:06.460 align:middle line:90%
to use this in a minute anyway.

00:25:06.460 --> 00:25:11.500 align:middle line:84%
So again, if you
take a set here--

00:25:11.500 --> 00:25:16.540 align:middle line:84%
so if you take a metric space,
and suppose you take a set,

00:25:16.540 --> 00:25:23.780 align:middle line:84%
a subset of x, then you can
always find a cover, even

00:25:23.780 --> 00:25:25.780 align:middle line:90%
an open cover.

00:25:25.780 --> 00:25:27.580 align:middle line:84%
And in particular,
in a minute, we

00:25:27.580 --> 00:25:31.420 align:middle line:84%
will look at-- so if
you take a here, so one

00:25:31.420 --> 00:25:35.340 align:middle line:84%
example of an open cover
of a, is that you're

00:25:35.340 --> 00:25:40.180 align:middle line:90%
looking at the family of balls.

00:25:40.180 --> 00:25:43.800 align:middle line:84%
You just pick some
radius r as positive,

00:25:43.800 --> 00:25:46.180 align:middle line:90%
And then you pick centers.

00:25:46.180 --> 00:25:48.880 align:middle line:90%


00:25:48.880 --> 00:25:50.040 align:middle line:90%
But the centers-- sorry.

00:25:50.040 --> 00:25:57.660 align:middle line:84%
You take the centers, x
here is now anything in a.

00:25:57.660 --> 00:26:00.900 align:middle line:90%
R is fixed, It's positive.

00:26:00.900 --> 00:26:04.060 align:middle line:90%
X is anything in a.

00:26:04.060 --> 00:26:07.020 align:middle line:84%
Well, the union of
these guys, the union

00:26:07.020 --> 00:26:09.720 align:middle line:90%
certainly contains the centers.

00:26:09.720 --> 00:26:14.250 align:middle line:90%
So this here already cover a.

00:26:14.250 --> 00:26:16.690 align:middle line:90%
And we will use this.

00:26:16.690 --> 00:26:18.910 align:middle line:84%
This is like a standard
way to get a cover.

00:26:18.910 --> 00:26:21.410 align:middle line:84%
And then if it's compact,
then finally, many of those

00:26:21.410 --> 00:26:23.530 align:middle line:90%
should cover.

00:26:23.530 --> 00:26:25.840 align:middle line:90%
So in fact, let's get to that.

00:26:25.840 --> 00:26:28.650 align:middle line:90%


00:26:28.650 --> 00:26:33.130 align:middle line:84%
So the next thing
I want to prove,

00:26:33.130 --> 00:26:44.960 align:middle line:84%
is this Bolzano-Weierstrass
version for a metric space.

00:26:44.960 --> 00:26:48.170 align:middle line:90%


00:26:48.170 --> 00:26:53.010 align:middle line:84%
So you prove a
Bolzano-Weierstrass theorem

00:26:53.010 --> 00:26:54.030 align:middle line:90%
for metric spaces.

00:26:54.030 --> 00:26:56.930 align:middle line:84%
Remember that the
Bolzano-Weierstrass does not

00:26:56.930 --> 00:26:58.440 align:middle line:90%
hold for every metric space--

00:26:58.440 --> 00:27:14.090 align:middle line:90%


00:27:14.090 --> 00:27:18.250 align:middle line:90%
for a metric space.

00:27:18.250 --> 00:27:22.370 align:middle line:84%
So now, the Bolzano-Weierstrass
does not hold for every metric

00:27:22.370 --> 00:27:23.890 align:middle line:90%
space, but it holds--

00:27:23.890 --> 00:27:30.900 align:middle line:84%
so when this space
here is compact.

00:27:30.900 --> 00:27:40.710 align:middle line:90%


00:27:40.710 --> 00:27:42.450 align:middle line:90%
So that's what I want to prove.

00:27:42.450 --> 00:27:44.530 align:middle line:84%
And that's one of
the motivations

00:27:44.530 --> 00:27:50.130 align:middle line:84%
here for the definition
of being compact.

00:27:50.130 --> 00:27:54.570 align:middle line:90%
And so let me just remind you.

00:27:54.570 --> 00:28:01.530 align:middle line:84%
So on Rn, on r, say, what
is the [? Balzani? ?]

00:28:01.530 --> 00:28:10.200 align:middle line:84%
So on r the Bolzano-Weierstrass
theorem, what did that say?

00:28:10.200 --> 00:28:15.440 align:middle line:84%
So this is that any
bounded sequence

00:28:15.440 --> 00:28:28.400 align:middle line:90%
has a convergent subsequence.

00:28:28.400 --> 00:28:33.140 align:middle line:90%


00:28:33.140 --> 00:28:35.380 align:middle line:84%
That was the
Bolzano-Weierstrass theorem.

00:28:35.380 --> 00:28:38.560 align:middle line:90%


00:28:38.560 --> 00:28:42.720 align:middle line:84%
And so what we
want to show here,

00:28:42.720 --> 00:28:47.450 align:middle line:84%
is the following theorem
for a general metric space.

00:28:47.450 --> 00:28:57.760 align:middle line:90%


00:28:57.760 --> 00:29:05.240 align:middle line:84%
So we want to prove the
following theorem that if x,d is

00:29:05.240 --> 00:29:16.040 align:middle line:90%
a metric space, a here is--

00:29:16.040 --> 00:29:17.490 align:middle line:90%
subset is compact.

00:29:17.490 --> 00:29:22.520 align:middle line:90%


00:29:22.520 --> 00:29:48.400 align:middle line:84%
Then any sequence in a has
a convergent subsequence.

00:29:48.400 --> 00:29:57.320 align:middle line:90%


00:29:57.320 --> 00:30:00.760 align:middle line:84%
Now, let me try to
divide it into two--

00:30:00.760 --> 00:30:04.410 align:middle line:84%
let me try to divide
it into some subpieces.

00:30:04.410 --> 00:30:09.150 align:middle line:90%


00:30:09.150 --> 00:30:17.030 align:middle line:90%
So I begin with a lemma.

00:30:17.030 --> 00:30:26.430 align:middle line:84%
So I want to begin with a
lemma that is the following.

00:30:26.430 --> 00:30:35.360 align:middle line:90%
So I have a my metric space.

00:30:35.360 --> 00:30:39.150 align:middle line:90%


00:30:39.150 --> 00:30:44.900 align:middle line:84%
I have a here is the
subset that is compact.

00:30:44.900 --> 00:30:50.350 align:middle line:90%


00:30:50.350 --> 00:30:55.250 align:middle line:84%
And then I have as a
family of nested subsets,

00:30:55.250 --> 00:30:59.420 align:middle line:84%
so let me just talk about
nested subsets for a second.

00:30:59.420 --> 00:31:05.550 align:middle line:90%


00:31:05.550 --> 00:31:08.350 align:middle line:90%
So I'll do this on this board.

00:31:08.350 --> 00:31:10.980 align:middle line:84%
So what do I mean
by nested subset?

00:31:10.980 --> 00:31:19.070 align:middle line:90%


00:31:19.070 --> 00:31:28.110 align:middle line:84%
So again, I have some set, and
then I have some subsets, c.

00:31:28.110 --> 00:31:34.470 align:middle line:84%
It's a family, but
it's now a family that

00:31:34.470 --> 00:31:38.990 align:middle line:90%
is indexed by the integers.

00:31:38.990 --> 00:31:44.310 align:middle line:90%
So Ci here, is subset.

00:31:44.310 --> 00:31:49.770 align:middle line:84%
So this is i equal
to 1, 2, and so on.

00:31:49.770 --> 00:31:53.890 align:middle line:90%


00:31:53.890 --> 00:31:58.070 align:middle line:84%
In this case here,
I am thinking about

00:31:58.070 --> 00:32:02.500 align:middle line:84%
that the next subset is
smaller than the previous,

00:32:02.500 --> 00:32:07.260 align:middle line:84%
smaller or at most
equal to the previous.

00:32:07.260 --> 00:32:09.500 align:middle line:90%
So I have this.

00:32:09.500 --> 00:32:11.860 align:middle line:84%
I could also have
looked at where

00:32:11.860 --> 00:32:13.840 align:middle line:84%
they were kind of
increasing the subsets,

00:32:13.840 --> 00:32:18.030 align:middle line:84%
but this here is
what I have in mind.

00:32:18.030 --> 00:32:21.100 align:middle line:90%


00:32:21.100 --> 00:32:27.800 align:middle line:84%
So the sets as I become larger,
the set becomes smaller.

00:32:27.800 --> 00:32:30.500 align:middle line:90%
So now back to the lemma.

00:32:30.500 --> 00:32:32.380 align:middle line:90%
I have this metric space.

00:32:32.380 --> 00:32:34.340 align:middle line:90%
I have a compact subset.

00:32:34.340 --> 00:32:42.860 align:middle line:84%
And then I have a sequence
here of Ci's is a sequence-- is

00:32:42.860 --> 00:32:53.780 align:middle line:90%
a nested sequence of subsets.

00:32:53.780 --> 00:32:57.500 align:middle line:84%
So again, this means
that the next element is

00:32:57.500 --> 00:33:00.970 align:middle line:90%
contained in the previous one.

00:33:00.970 --> 00:33:04.310 align:middle line:84%
And this nested
sequence of subsets,

00:33:04.310 --> 00:33:11.650 align:middle line:84%
it's actually a nested
sequence of closed subsets,

00:33:11.650 --> 00:33:16.690 align:middle line:90%
closed subsets of a.

00:33:16.690 --> 00:33:24.810 align:middle line:84%
So they're closed in x,
and they're contained in a.

00:33:24.810 --> 00:33:29.850 align:middle line:90%
And then I am assuming that--

00:33:29.850 --> 00:33:42.570 align:middle line:90%
and assume also that the Ci's--

00:33:42.570 --> 00:33:46.010 align:middle line:84%
that none of the Ci's
are the empty sets.

00:33:46.010 --> 00:33:52.410 align:middle line:84%
So I don't want any
of them to be trivial.

00:33:52.410 --> 00:33:53.790 align:middle line:90%
Then the claim is--

00:33:53.790 --> 00:33:59.610 align:middle line:84%
so the claim is that
if that's the case,

00:33:59.610 --> 00:34:05.570 align:middle line:84%
then actually, if you take the
intersection of all of these,

00:34:05.570 --> 00:34:08.070 align:middle line:90%
this here is non-empty.

00:34:08.070 --> 00:34:13.690 align:middle line:84%
So there is something that
is in all of the Ci's.

00:34:13.690 --> 00:34:16.889 align:middle line:90%
That's what I want to prove.

00:34:16.889 --> 00:34:21.230 align:middle line:84%
And in fact, this is
quite straightforward.

00:34:21.230 --> 00:34:25.330 align:middle line:90%


00:34:25.330 --> 00:34:29.650 align:middle line:90%
And because since the--

00:34:29.650 --> 00:34:42.730 align:middle line:84%
so the proof here,
since Ci is closed,

00:34:42.730 --> 00:34:48.429 align:middle line:84%
this means that the
complement here is open.

00:34:48.429 --> 00:34:54.290 align:middle line:90%


00:34:54.290 --> 00:34:57.520 align:middle line:84%
And now for the
complements here--

00:34:57.520 --> 00:35:00.560 align:middle line:84%
so the complement,
let's call it--

00:35:00.560 --> 00:35:05.040 align:middle line:84%
the compliments,
let's call it Bi.

00:35:05.040 --> 00:35:06.820 align:middle line:90%
So Bi is open again.

00:35:06.820 --> 00:35:14.600 align:middle line:84%
And Bi plus 1, they
actually have this property

00:35:14.600 --> 00:35:18.840 align:middle line:84%
that they are because the
previous ones was nested

00:35:18.840 --> 00:35:21.040 align:middle line:90%
where they became smaller.

00:35:21.040 --> 00:35:23.540 align:middle line:84%
Then when you're looking
at the complements,

00:35:23.540 --> 00:35:24.540 align:middle line:90%
then they become larger.

00:35:24.540 --> 00:35:30.800 align:middle line:90%


00:35:30.800 --> 00:35:35.120 align:middle line:84%
So since this is closed,
then we have this.

00:35:35.120 --> 00:35:40.400 align:middle line:84%
If the intersection
of these Ci, if there

00:35:40.400 --> 00:35:44.720 align:middle line:84%
was nothing in the
intersection of all of them,

00:35:44.720 --> 00:35:49.000 align:middle line:84%
if this here was the
empty set, but then it

00:35:49.000 --> 00:35:56.920 align:middle line:84%
means that the complement of
these guys would then cover a.

00:35:56.920 --> 00:35:59.880 align:middle line:84%
It would actually bind the
cover because there's nothing--

00:35:59.880 --> 00:36:02.280 align:middle line:90%
the union of the complement.

00:36:02.280 --> 00:36:04.460 align:middle line:84%
So the union of the
complement here.

00:36:04.460 --> 00:36:07.240 align:middle line:90%


00:36:07.240 --> 00:36:14.080 align:middle line:84%
They would actually cover x, but
it would in particular cover a.

00:36:14.080 --> 00:36:17.240 align:middle line:90%
So this here called bi.

00:36:17.240 --> 00:36:20.280 align:middle line:90%
So you have that.

00:36:20.280 --> 00:36:27.400 align:middle line:84%
So this mean-- and again, this
here, this is the same as bi.

00:36:27.400 --> 00:36:30.250 align:middle line:90%
So now since a is compact--

00:36:30.250 --> 00:36:37.080 align:middle line:90%


00:36:37.080 --> 00:36:49.240 align:middle line:84%
since a is compact, this
means that a here is contained

00:36:49.240 --> 00:36:53.200 align:middle line:90%
in finitely many of these.

00:36:53.200 --> 00:36:59.730 align:middle line:84%
Let's call them-- so you
have finitely many like this

00:36:59.730 --> 00:37:01.450 align:middle line:90%
of the B's.

00:37:01.450 --> 00:37:05.270 align:middle line:84%
And I'm not sure
whether it's the first,

00:37:05.270 --> 00:37:08.930 align:middle line:84%
but there are finitely many
of these that cover it.

00:37:08.930 --> 00:37:11.750 align:middle line:90%


00:37:11.750 --> 00:37:15.430 align:middle line:84%
And so in particular
by one of these

00:37:15.430 --> 00:37:18.470 align:middle line:84%
is like by one of
the indices here

00:37:18.470 --> 00:37:21.390 align:middle line:90%
is the largest one of those.

00:37:21.390 --> 00:37:24.430 align:middle line:84%
And so this means that
it's actually contained

00:37:24.430 --> 00:37:26.310 align:middle line:90%
in the largest of these.

00:37:26.310 --> 00:37:33.270 align:middle line:84%
Let's say that the
largest of these is Bn.

00:37:33.270 --> 00:37:36.950 align:middle line:90%
So you have this for some n.

00:37:36.950 --> 00:37:40.990 align:middle line:84%
But this here, remember
that this here was

00:37:40.990 --> 00:37:46.950 align:middle line:90%
the complement of Cn like this.

00:37:46.950 --> 00:37:53.390 align:middle line:84%
So this means that a
have nothing in Cn.

00:37:53.390 --> 00:37:54.710 align:middle line:90%
But a was a--

00:37:54.710 --> 00:38:00.350 align:middle line:90%
Cn intersected with a.

00:38:00.350 --> 00:38:01.590 align:middle line:90%
It's empty.

00:38:01.590 --> 00:38:04.390 align:middle line:90%
But Cn was contained in a.

00:38:04.390 --> 00:38:13.310 align:middle line:84%
So this means that since Cn was
assumed to be contained in a,

00:38:13.310 --> 00:38:19.510 align:middle line:84%
