00:53:05.980 --> 00:53:08.140 align:middle line:84%
So this means that
this implies--

00:53:08.140 --> 00:53:13.820 align:middle line:84%
as you say, this implies that
the distance had to be 0.

00:53:13.820 --> 00:53:15.700 align:middle line:84%
But this is part
of what it means

00:53:15.700 --> 00:53:19.180 align:middle line:84%
to be a metric space that
if the distance is 0,

00:53:19.180 --> 00:53:22.140 align:middle line:84%
then the two points
are the same.

00:53:22.140 --> 00:53:26.220 align:middle line:84%
So the whole
[INAUDIBLE] was really

00:53:26.220 --> 00:53:30.300 align:middle line:90%
quite easy from the lemma.

00:53:30.300 --> 00:53:32.300 align:middle line:84%
And so now the
question is-- so this

00:53:32.300 --> 00:53:35.660 align:middle line:84%
is your question is,
why is this relevant

00:53:35.660 --> 00:53:39.935 align:middle line:90%
in this Bolzano-Weierstrass?

00:53:39.935 --> 00:53:42.900 align:middle line:84%
I mean, they may be not so
interesting, I mean, the lemma

00:53:42.900 --> 00:53:46.540 align:middle line:84%
and the [INAUDIBLE]
on its own, but there

00:53:46.540 --> 00:53:50.410 align:middle line:84%
are tools to prove this
Bolzano-Weierstrass theorem.

00:53:50.410 --> 00:53:53.180 align:middle line:90%


00:53:53.180 --> 00:54:03.360 align:middle line:84%
So let me try to first
explain the idea.

00:54:03.360 --> 00:54:07.500 align:middle line:90%
And then we go to the proof.

00:54:07.500 --> 00:54:14.020 align:middle line:90%
So we have this metric space.

00:54:14.020 --> 00:54:17.340 align:middle line:90%
And we have a subset.

00:54:17.340 --> 00:54:20.606 align:middle line:90%
And the subset here is compact.

00:54:20.606 --> 00:54:23.000 align:middle line:84%
A subset is assumed
to be compact.

00:54:23.000 --> 00:54:26.690 align:middle line:90%


00:54:26.690 --> 00:54:31.690 align:middle line:90%
Then we have a sequence Xn.

00:54:31.690 --> 00:54:33.770 align:middle line:90%
And the sequence here--

00:54:33.770 --> 00:54:48.890 align:middle line:84%
so this is a sequence
contained in A.

00:54:48.890 --> 00:54:53.350 align:middle line:84%
And we want to prove
that there exists--

00:54:53.350 --> 00:54:55.050 align:middle line:90%
so I want to show--

00:54:55.050 --> 00:55:06.410 align:middle line:84%
want to find a
convergent subsequence.

00:55:06.410 --> 00:55:09.490 align:middle line:90%


00:55:09.490 --> 00:55:12.250 align:middle line:84%
Remember that here-- I
mean, just that there's no

00:55:12.250 --> 00:55:13.570 align:middle line:90%
assumption--

00:55:13.570 --> 00:55:17.810 align:middle line:84%
I'm not talking about
some Cauchy complete set

00:55:17.810 --> 00:55:19.690 align:middle line:90%
space or something like that.

00:55:19.690 --> 00:55:22.610 align:middle line:84%
So in this case, I really
have to construct the--

00:55:22.610 --> 00:55:26.250 align:middle line:84%
I have to construct the
convergence sequence.

00:55:26.250 --> 00:55:29.490 align:middle line:84%
But I also have to
construct the limits.

00:55:29.490 --> 00:55:34.890 align:middle line:84%
And so this is where in
particular, like the limit,

00:55:34.890 --> 00:55:36.970 align:middle line:84%
this is why we want
this thing here

00:55:36.970 --> 00:55:41.730 align:middle line:90%
to have a unique intersection.

00:55:41.730 --> 00:55:43.910 align:middle line:90%
So that's what I want to do.

00:55:43.910 --> 00:55:46.970 align:middle line:90%
So you have this space.

00:55:46.970 --> 00:55:49.170 align:middle line:84%
You have the subset
that's compact.

00:55:49.170 --> 00:55:52.410 align:middle line:90%
And you are given a sequence.

00:55:52.410 --> 00:55:59.770 align:middle line:84%
So and before I actually
get to the proof,

00:55:59.770 --> 00:56:01.960 align:middle line:84%
let me just try to
explain the idea.

00:56:01.960 --> 00:56:10.010 align:middle line:90%


00:56:10.010 --> 00:56:14.840 align:middle line:84%
So again, this is
before the proof.

00:56:14.840 --> 00:56:23.360 align:middle line:90%


00:56:23.360 --> 00:56:25.380 align:middle line:84%
So I want to make
an observation.

00:56:25.380 --> 00:56:29.080 align:middle line:84%
So if I am in this
iteration, and suppose

00:56:29.080 --> 00:56:34.960 align:middle line:84%
now that I take-- so I have
A here, and I take some r,

00:56:34.960 --> 00:56:37.640 align:middle line:84%
sigma of r is
being really small,

00:56:37.640 --> 00:56:41.400 align:middle line:84%
and then do what we just
did a little while ago.

00:56:41.400 --> 00:56:44.360 align:middle line:90%
We cover.

00:56:44.360 --> 00:56:50.320 align:middle line:84%
We're looking at
A here is covered.

00:56:50.320 --> 00:56:53.760 align:middle line:84%
You can write as A as
a union of these balls

00:56:53.760 --> 00:56:58.480 align:middle line:84%
here, where the center
is anything in A.

00:56:58.480 --> 00:57:03.570 align:middle line:84%
So again, that cover A-- and so
this means that finitely many--

00:57:03.570 --> 00:57:06.120 align:middle line:90%


00:57:06.120 --> 00:57:18.750 align:middle line:84%
that's finitely many cover
A since A is compact.

00:57:18.750 --> 00:57:23.080 align:middle line:90%


00:57:23.080 --> 00:57:31.660 align:middle line:84%
So I can write A here as
contained in and then r--

00:57:31.660 --> 00:57:34.037 align:middle line:90%


00:57:34.037 --> 00:57:35.120 align:middle line:90%
now, I have to be careful.

00:57:35.120 --> 00:57:37.500 align:middle line:90%
Because this is not the x.

00:57:37.500 --> 00:57:41.040 align:middle line:84%
Probably, I should use a
y here, sorry, just to not

00:57:41.040 --> 00:57:45.960 align:middle line:84%
confuse it with the
sequence that I have, OK.

00:57:45.960 --> 00:57:58.200 align:middle line:84%
And so it's contained in the
union of balls like this, Ym.

00:57:58.200 --> 00:58:03.160 align:middle line:84%
Y is contained in the union of
finitely many balls like this.

00:58:03.160 --> 00:58:06.320 align:middle line:84%
OK, so far we haven't
used our sequence.

00:58:06.320 --> 00:58:12.560 align:middle line:84%
But now, of course, I can say
that we were given a sequence.

00:58:12.560 --> 00:58:16.798 align:middle line:90%
We now have finitely many balls.

00:58:16.798 --> 00:58:20.050 align:middle line:84%
And there are infinitely many
elements in the sequence.

00:58:20.050 --> 00:58:23.290 align:middle line:84%
So it means that there
is one of these balls,

00:58:23.290 --> 00:58:26.210 align:middle line:84%
finitely many balls,
so for one of them--

00:58:26.210 --> 00:58:28.910 align:middle line:90%


00:58:28.910 --> 00:58:32.170 align:middle line:84%
for one, maybe more than
1, maybe all of them.

00:58:32.170 --> 00:58:41.590 align:middle line:84%
But for at least for
one of these balls,

00:58:41.590 --> 00:58:56.220 align:middle line:84%
there are infinitely many
elements in the sequence.

00:58:56.220 --> 00:58:58.990 align:middle line:90%


00:58:58.990 --> 00:59:01.410 align:middle line:84%
Let me be very precise
what I mean by that.

00:59:01.410 --> 00:59:04.210 align:middle line:90%


00:59:04.210 --> 00:59:06.850 align:middle line:84%
Of course, the sequence could
be like a constant sequence.

00:59:06.850 --> 00:59:11.470 align:middle line:84%
What I mean that for
infinitely many n's Xn

00:59:11.470 --> 00:59:14.270 align:middle line:90%
is in one of these balls.

00:59:14.270 --> 00:59:15.790 align:middle line:84%
So let me just write
that out, Just.

00:59:15.790 --> 00:59:18.030 align:middle line:90%
To be totally clear.

00:59:18.030 --> 00:59:33.670 align:middle line:84%
So meaning for one
of these balls,

00:59:33.670 --> 00:59:44.570 align:middle line:84%
