cover this.

01:11:26.022 --> 01:11:27.480 align:middle line:84%
But it means, of
course, that there

01:11:27.480 --> 01:11:29.600 align:middle line:90%
could be something outside.

01:11:29.600 --> 01:11:31.800 align:middle line:90%
There could be.

01:11:31.800 --> 01:11:35.800 align:middle line:84%
So this is like a
ball of radius r.

01:11:35.800 --> 01:11:39.860 align:middle line:84%
And so then you have this
ball of radius a quarter r.

01:11:39.860 --> 01:11:43.720 align:middle line:84%
But the quarter balls, they
may have some part outside

01:11:43.720 --> 01:11:45.180 align:middle line:90%
and some part inside.

01:11:45.180 --> 01:11:49.280 align:middle line:90%
So it's not this ball here.

01:11:49.280 --> 01:11:51.680 align:middle line:90%
It's not contained in that ball.

01:11:51.680 --> 01:11:55.840 align:middle line:84%
But if you went to
the double ball,

01:11:55.840 --> 01:11:58.900 align:middle line:84%
if you went to this
ball of radius 2r,

01:11:58.900 --> 01:12:07.900 align:middle line:84%
you see this point here, the
center here, it would lie--

01:12:07.900 --> 01:12:11.000 align:middle line:84%
there would be some
points in this ball here

01:12:11.000 --> 01:12:13.000 align:middle line:90%
that would be within.

01:12:13.000 --> 01:12:15.560 align:middle line:84%
It may not be the center,
but there's some point here

01:12:15.560 --> 01:12:19.440 align:middle line:90%
that's within r of the center.

01:12:19.440 --> 01:12:21.920 align:middle line:84%
And then by the
triangle inequality,

01:12:21.920 --> 01:12:25.640 align:middle line:84%
any other points is
actually within r 2,

01:12:25.640 --> 01:12:28.760 align:middle line:90%
r over 2 of that point.

01:12:28.760 --> 01:12:31.520 align:middle line:90%
So everything is comfortably--

01:12:31.520 --> 01:12:35.600 align:middle line:84%
so this thing here and
even the half ball--

01:12:35.600 --> 01:12:42.520 align:middle line:84%
so I can conclude that
even the ball of radius

01:12:42.520 --> 01:12:45.660 align:middle line:90%
r over 2, even this one here.

01:12:45.660 --> 01:12:48.240 align:middle line:90%


01:12:48.240 --> 01:12:57.650 align:middle line:84%
Is contained in the
double ball like that.

01:12:57.650 --> 01:13:00.890 align:middle line:90%


01:13:00.890 --> 01:13:07.390 align:middle line:84%
And in fact, if you make things
less or equal to on both things,

01:13:07.390 --> 01:13:08.410 align:middle line:90%
then you have that.

01:13:08.410 --> 01:13:11.985 align:middle line:90%


01:13:11.985 --> 01:13:13.590 align:middle line:90%
Now what I have is--

01:13:13.590 --> 01:13:21.190 align:middle line:84%
at least here you have
something that is nested.

01:13:21.190 --> 01:13:26.510 align:middle line:84%
And you see that the
radius went down.

01:13:26.510 --> 01:13:29.470 align:middle line:84%
So these are nested,
and they are closed.

01:13:29.470 --> 01:13:34.030 align:middle line:84%
And so now what
we do is-- so now

01:13:34.030 --> 01:13:38.290 align:middle line:84%
we want to do this
for a sequence.

01:13:38.290 --> 01:13:40.870 align:middle line:84%
And then of course,
we want to-- so now we

01:13:40.870 --> 01:13:44.530 align:middle line:84%
want to construct a sequence
of closed balls like this.

01:13:44.530 --> 01:13:47.040 align:middle line:90%


01:13:47.040 --> 01:13:50.340 align:middle line:84%
And now when you pick
your subsequence,

01:13:50.340 --> 01:13:55.820 align:middle line:84%
you can't wait with picking the
first element in subsequence.

01:13:55.820 --> 01:13:57.940 align:middle line:84%
Remember, if you keep
waiting, then you

01:13:57.940 --> 01:13:59.620 align:middle line:90%
will end up getting nothing.

01:13:59.620 --> 01:14:02.540 align:middle line:84%
So you pick-- at
each stage, you pick

01:14:02.540 --> 01:14:04.740 align:middle line:90%
one element in the subsequence.

01:14:04.740 --> 01:14:06.680 align:middle line:84%
And then when you
have the next ball,

01:14:06.680 --> 01:14:11.075 align:middle line:84%
you pick the next element
in the subsequent and so on.

01:14:11.075 --> 01:14:17.020 align:middle line:90%
And so we will do this with--

01:14:17.020 --> 01:14:19.480 align:middle line:84%
so we're going to do
this procedure here.

01:14:19.480 --> 01:14:22.880 align:middle line:84%
So now we're getting back
to the proof of the theorem.

01:14:22.880 --> 01:14:25.380 align:middle line:84%
And again, remember the
theorem was this-- maybe

01:14:25.380 --> 01:14:27.460 align:middle line:90%
I erased it now by mistake.

01:14:27.460 --> 01:14:30.340 align:middle line:84%
But the theorem was this
Bolzano-Weierstrass theorem

01:14:30.340 --> 01:14:31.700 align:middle line:90%
for a metric space.

01:14:31.700 --> 01:14:34.900 align:middle line:84%
If you have a metric space,
you have a compact subset,

01:14:34.900 --> 01:14:37.900 align:middle line:84%
and you have a sequence
in this compact subset.

01:14:37.900 --> 01:14:42.100 align:middle line:84%
And you want to construct
a convergent subsequence.

01:14:42.100 --> 01:14:45.700 align:middle line:90%
So what you do is--

01:14:45.700 --> 01:14:51.900 align:middle line:84%
that's a proof of the
Bolzano-Weierstrass

01:14:51.900 --> 01:14:52.850 align:middle line:90%
for metric spaces.

01:14:52.850 --> 01:14:59.700 align:middle line:90%


01:14:59.700 --> 01:15:02.460 align:middle line:84%
So what you do is--
so you have this.

01:15:02.460 --> 01:15:06.700 align:middle line:84%
Again, A here is compact,
and you have a sequence Xn.

01:15:06.700 --> 01:15:09.100 align:middle line:84%
This is a sequence
that is contained

01:15:09.100 --> 01:15:13.740 align:middle line:84%
in A. What you do
is that first you

01:15:13.740 --> 01:15:18.140 align:middle line:90%
can just let r be equal to 1.

01:15:18.140 --> 01:15:20.820 align:middle line:90%
And then you do this.

01:15:20.820 --> 01:15:24.940 align:middle line:90%
You cover it by--

01:15:24.940 --> 01:15:26.220 align:middle line:90%
you cover it.

01:15:26.220 --> 01:15:29.180 align:middle line:84%
You have here A.
And you cover it

01:15:29.180 --> 01:15:33.940 align:middle line:84%
by finitely many
balls of radius 1.

01:15:33.940 --> 01:15:37.900 align:middle line:84%
And for one of these balls, you
have that there's infinitely

01:15:37.900 --> 01:15:40.020 align:middle line:90%
many element in the sequence.

01:15:40.020 --> 01:15:43.970 align:middle line:84%
So you're going to focus on
that ball from here on and out.

01:15:43.970 --> 01:15:45.570 align:middle line:90%
And you just pick--

01:15:45.570 --> 01:15:49.010 align:middle line:84%
in your subsequence, you
now pick your first element

01:15:49.010 --> 01:15:54.730 align:middle line:84%
in the subsequence to be
some element in that ball.

01:15:54.730 --> 01:15:59.090 align:middle line:84%
So now the picture is that
you just look at that ball.

01:15:59.090 --> 01:16:02.810 align:middle line:84%
Forget about the other
ball and everything else.

01:16:02.810 --> 01:16:09.330 align:middle line:84%
You now cover it by balls
of radius a quarter.

01:16:09.330 --> 01:16:12.690 align:middle line:90%
And you have that--

01:16:12.690 --> 01:16:16.610 align:middle line:84%
again, that's
finitely many cover--

01:16:16.610 --> 01:16:22.250 align:middle line:84%
this ball intersected with
A, finitely many cover it.

01:16:22.250 --> 01:16:27.650 align:middle line:84%
And so one of them has
infinitely many elements

01:16:27.650 --> 01:16:32.290 align:middle line:84%
in this subsequence
you consider.

01:16:32.290 --> 01:16:35.710 align:middle line:84%
And so you just pick
one element in that.

01:16:35.710 --> 01:16:38.730 align:middle line:90%
That's the next one.

01:16:38.730 --> 01:16:41.390 align:middle line:90%
And now you repeat this process.

01:16:41.390 --> 01:16:43.870 align:middle line:84%
And so you see that
for these balls--

01:16:43.870 --> 01:16:47.690 align:middle line:84%
but remember that-- so you're
starting with the radius 1.

01:16:47.690 --> 01:16:50.310 align:middle line:90%
But you have to double things.

01:16:50.310 --> 01:16:55.050 align:middle line:84%
So the sequence of closed
sets, the initial closed sets,

01:16:55.050 --> 01:16:57.450 align:middle line:90%
will have radius 2.

01:16:57.450 --> 01:17:01.930 align:middle line:84%
And the next one won't
have radius a quarter,

01:17:01.930 --> 01:17:06.550 align:middle line:84%
but it will have radius 2
times a quarter, so one half.

01:17:06.550 --> 01:17:09.630 align:middle line:84%
And the next one
will then be a ball.

01:17:09.630 --> 01:17:11.610 align:middle line:84%
It will have a
different center, and it

01:17:11.610 --> 01:17:13.330 align:middle line:90%
will have radius one half.

01:17:13.330 --> 01:17:16.050 align:middle line:84%
And then the next one
you see, at each stage

01:17:16.050 --> 01:17:21.770 align:middle line:84%
when I do it like this, then
it goes down with a factor of 4

01:17:21.770 --> 01:17:23.070 align:middle line:90%
at each stage.

01:17:23.070 --> 01:17:26.910 align:middle line:84%
So this here would be
1 over 8 and so on.

01:17:26.910 --> 01:17:32.050 align:middle line:84%
And so you see that this
sequence, these closed balls,

01:17:32.050 --> 01:17:35.210 align:middle line:84%
they are nested
as they should be.

01:17:35.210 --> 01:17:38.370 align:middle line:90%
And the radii goes to zero.

01:17:38.370 --> 01:17:41.560 align:middle line:84%
So this means that
there is an element that

01:17:41.560 --> 01:17:46.360 align:middle line:84%
lies in all of these, and
that is now the limit because

01:17:46.360 --> 01:17:48.800 align:middle line:90%
of the subsequence.

01:17:48.800 --> 01:17:53.400 align:middle line:84%
From here on and out, it would
be in that ball and from it

01:17:53.400 --> 01:17:56.360 align:middle line:84%
later on and out, it
would be in the next ball.

01:17:56.360 --> 01:18:01.140 align:middle line:84%
So that intersection of all of
these balls will be your limit.

01:18:01.140 --> 01:18:02.430 align:middle line:90%
Yeah?

01:18:02.430 --> 01:18:05.280 align:middle line:90%
AUDIENCE: [INAUDIBLE]

01:18:05.280 --> 01:18:10.040 align:middle line:90%


01:18:10.040 --> 01:18:12.120 align:middle line:84%
TOBIAS COLDING: So
really what you're

01:18:12.120 --> 01:18:18.680 align:middle line:84%
looking at that this thing
here, it's intersected with A.

01:18:18.680 --> 01:18:23.560 align:middle line:84%
So it's just that these balls
here, so the intersection here,

01:18:23.560 --> 01:18:28.060 align:middle line:84%
that these are the closed sets,
and these are the compacts.

01:18:28.060 --> 01:18:30.600 align:middle line:84%
They are each of
them are non-empty.

01:18:30.600 --> 01:18:35.200 align:middle line:84%
And they are the
closed subsets of A.

01:18:35.200 --> 01:18:38.200 align:middle line:84%
So you're really arguing
on these guys here.

01:18:38.200 --> 01:18:40.760 align:middle line:90%
You see what I mean?

01:18:40.760 --> 01:18:44.420 align:middle line:84%
I know I stated it for
balls in the column.

01:18:44.420 --> 01:18:47.800 align:middle line:84%
But if you just think
about it, the balls

01:18:47.800 --> 01:18:50.560 align:middle line:84%
play no particular
role, except for saying

01:18:50.560 --> 01:18:54.460 align:middle line:84%
that the intersection of all
of them contain just one point.

01:18:54.460 --> 01:18:57.180 align:middle line:84%
And that was because
the radii went to zero.

01:18:57.180 --> 01:19:01.120 align:middle line:84%
The important points were that
the sets were closed subsets.

01:19:01.120 --> 01:19:03.960 align:middle line:84%
Because then there was the
lemma was just all about closed

01:19:03.960 --> 01:19:04.500 align:middle line:90%
subset.

01:19:04.500 --> 01:19:06.320 align:middle line:90%
It had nothing to do with--

01:19:06.320 --> 01:19:16.040 align:middle line:84%
And so you see that these guys
here are closed subsets of A.

01:19:16.040 --> 01:19:17.880 align:middle line:90%
And so--

01:19:17.880 --> 01:19:20.204 align:middle line:90%
yeah?

01:19:20.204 --> 01:19:21.660 align:middle line:84%
AUDIENCE: I don't
quite understand

01:19:21.660 --> 01:19:23.640 align:middle line:90%
where the [INAUDIBLE].

01:19:23.640 --> 01:19:26.080 align:middle line:84%
Is it, you're looking
at the ball of radius 1

01:19:26.080 --> 01:19:29.320 align:middle line:84%
and trying to see how to
contain the ball of radius 1.

01:19:29.320 --> 01:19:32.495 align:middle line:84%
TOBIAS COLDING: You mean why
I went to double the ball, no?

01:19:32.495 --> 01:19:33.120 align:middle line:90%
AUDIENCE: Yeah.

01:19:33.120 --> 01:19:37.430 align:middle line:84%
TOBIAS COLDING: OK, so the
reason I go to the double ball,

01:19:37.430 --> 01:19:40.710 align:middle line:84%
is that I want to make sure
that things are nested.

01:19:40.710 --> 01:19:48.150 align:middle line:84%
And if I just did this
procedure-- suppose so again,

01:19:48.150 --> 01:19:50.350 align:middle line:90%
I take this ball here.

01:19:50.350 --> 01:19:51.650 align:middle line:90%
This is the first step.

01:19:51.650 --> 01:19:54.790 align:middle line:90%
I have these balls of radius 1.

01:19:54.790 --> 01:19:57.070 align:middle line:84%
And I find one of
them so that there's

01:19:57.070 --> 01:19:59.270 align:middle line:90%
infinite many in the sequence.

01:19:59.270 --> 01:20:02.950 align:middle line:84%
Then I want to have
something finer.

01:20:02.950 --> 01:20:05.590 align:middle line:90%
And so I go to--

01:20:05.590 --> 01:20:07.790 align:middle line:84%
I chose because I
think-- you didn't quite

01:20:07.790 --> 01:20:08.930 align:middle line:90%
have to do a quarter.

01:20:08.930 --> 01:20:10.930 align:middle line:84%
You could actually have
gotten away with a half,

01:20:10.930 --> 01:20:13.650 align:middle line:84%
but I thought it wasn't
as clear if I did it.

01:20:13.650 --> 01:20:15.510 align:middle line:84%
So I did it with a
quarter because then I

01:20:15.510 --> 01:20:18.070 align:middle line:90%
thought it looked more obvious.

01:20:18.070 --> 01:20:23.170 align:middle line:84%
So if you now take this
ball here, and as you say,

01:20:23.170 --> 01:20:28.150 align:middle line:84%
you always have to
intersect with A, just

01:20:28.150 --> 01:20:29.470 align:middle line:90%
to make things compact.

01:20:29.470 --> 01:20:36.510 align:middle line:84%
So I cover it with balls
of radius a quarter.

01:20:36.510 --> 01:20:42.250 align:middle line:84%
But some of these balls, part
of it may lie outside this ball

01:20:42.250 --> 01:20:42.750 align:middle line:90%
here.

01:20:42.750 --> 01:20:45.590 align:middle line:90%
Because I couldn't cover--

01:20:45.590 --> 01:20:48.070 align:middle line:84%
you see what I mean,
if I take a ball here.

01:20:48.070 --> 01:20:51.970 align:middle line:84%
I can't cover it by
finitely many balls.

01:20:51.970 --> 01:20:54.090 align:middle line:84%
Just if it was like
Euclidean space,

01:20:54.090 --> 01:20:56.950 align:middle line:84%
if I insist that the ball
had to be-- this smaller ball

01:20:56.950 --> 01:21:00.170 align:middle line:84%
had to be inside this ball, then
there wouldn't be finitely many.

01:21:00.170 --> 01:21:04.870 align:middle line:84%
So I have to look at balls
where some of these balls

01:21:04.870 --> 01:21:07.550 align:middle line:90%
is kind of outside the surface.

01:21:07.550 --> 01:21:10.390 align:middle line:84%
But now, of course, so
that wouldn't really

01:21:10.390 --> 01:21:13.210 align:middle line:84%
work because it's not
like this ball here,

01:21:13.210 --> 01:21:15.050 align:middle line:84%
let alone the
double of this ball.

01:21:15.050 --> 01:21:16.910 align:middle line:90%
It's not contained in this.

01:21:16.910 --> 01:21:19.390 align:middle line:84%
So that's why I
doubled that ball.

01:21:19.390 --> 01:21:24.830 align:middle line:84%
Then everything is comfortably
contained [INAUDIBLE].

01:21:24.830 --> 01:21:26.950 align:middle line:90%
Any other questions?

01:21:26.950 --> 01:21:27.830 align:middle line:90%
Yeah?

01:21:27.830 --> 01:21:30.090 align:middle line:84%
AUDIENCE: Since they're all
closed ball-- or wait, no.

01:21:30.090 --> 01:21:32.860 align:middle line:90%
These are open balls?

01:21:32.860 --> 01:21:34.620 align:middle line:84%
TOBIAS COLDING:
When I cover things,

01:21:34.620 --> 01:21:36.840 align:middle line:84%
they are open because
I have to have--

01:21:36.840 --> 01:21:41.380 align:middle line:84%
when I have a compact set, I
have to cover it by open subset.

01:21:41.380 --> 01:21:44.720 align:middle line:84%
But then once I'm looking
at the nested things,

01:21:44.720 --> 01:21:47.860 align:middle line:84%
I have to go to the closure,
because otherwise the lemma

01:21:47.860 --> 01:21:49.560 align:middle line:90%
and the corner would not apply.

01:21:49.560 --> 01:21:50.460 align:middle line:90%
AUDIENCE: OK.

01:21:50.460 --> 01:21:51.410 align:middle line:90%
TOBIAS COLDING: OK.

01:21:51.410 --> 01:21:53.660 align:middle line:84%
AUDIENCE: And [INAUDIBLE],
if they were closed though,

01:21:53.660 --> 01:21:59.202 align:middle line:84%
you would be able to
cover like E1 with a--

01:21:59.202 --> 01:22:00.660 align:middle line:84%
TOBIAS COLDING:
And I'm just saying

01:22:00.660 --> 01:22:04.620 align:middle line:84%
that if the open balls
cover it, then of course,

01:22:04.620 --> 01:22:08.140 align:middle line:84%
their closure also cover it
because the closure is a larger

01:22:08.140 --> 01:22:08.860 align:middle line:90%
set.

01:22:08.860 --> 01:22:09.976 align:middle line:90%
AUDIENCE: Yeah.

01:22:09.976 --> 01:22:12.580 align:middle line:84%
TOBIAS COLDING: But it
wouldn't be a priori clear

01:22:12.580 --> 01:22:16.480 align:middle line:84%
that-- it's not like
they're closed set.

01:22:16.480 --> 01:22:19.480 align:middle line:84%
So that it's not
working, the definition.

01:22:19.480 --> 01:22:20.860 align:middle line:90%
Yeah?

01:22:20.860 --> 01:22:22.700 align:middle line:84%
AUDIENCE: I'm not
sure if you have proof

01:22:22.700 --> 01:22:27.300 align:middle line:84%
that up there we have that
if you have a compact subset,

01:22:27.300 --> 01:22:29.645 align:middle line:84%
and you take the intersection
with a closed subset.

01:22:29.645 --> 01:22:31.020 align:middle line:84%
Yeah, we proved
that it's closed.

01:22:31.020 --> 01:22:32.168 align:middle line:90%
Can we prove it is compact?

01:22:32.168 --> 01:22:33.960 align:middle line:84%
TOBIAS COLDING: We
prove that it's compact.

01:22:33.960 --> 01:22:37.740 align:middle line:84%
And I can prove it again
because it's very easy.

01:22:37.740 --> 01:22:55.100 align:middle line:84%
So if you have a metric
space, this here is compact.

01:22:55.100 --> 01:22:58.540 align:middle line:84%
And now you take a
subset here of this here.

01:22:58.540 --> 01:23:01.420 align:middle line:90%
And this here is closed.

01:23:01.420 --> 01:23:04.980 align:middle line:90%
It's a closed subset of X.

01:23:04.980 --> 01:23:10.860 align:middle line:84%
Then you look at X take away
B. You take any cover of this.

01:23:10.860 --> 01:23:15.360 align:middle line:84%
Together with this, they cover
A. But then finitely many--

01:23:15.360 --> 01:23:19.020 align:middle line:84%
but this here have nothing in
B. So actually finitely many

01:23:19.020 --> 01:23:21.700 align:middle line:90%
of the other one cover B here.

01:23:21.700 --> 01:23:24.620 align:middle line:90%
Any other questions?

01:23:24.620 --> 01:23:27.230 align:middle line:90%
OK, great, thanks.

01:23:27.230 --> 01:23:30.000 align:middle line:90%